    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "I'm not sure I understand. You mean nesting the hoc? Since a base model can\nhave multiple variants there is a range of values for an attribute in the\ndata model. The base model might have 3 bedrooms and it might have 4\nvariants one with 4 bedrooms, one with 5, another with 4, and one with 6.\nSo then in the algolia record there​ is a minBedrooms attribute of 3 and a\nmaxBedrooms attribute of 6. Does your solution cover this use case or does\nit only work for a single variant?\n\nOn Tue, May 16, 2017, 9:21 AM Marie-Laure Thuret <notifications@github.com>\nwrote:\n\n> @mvanlonden <https://github.com/mvanlonden>: in that case, isn't it\n> possible to use multiple connectRange?\n>\n> One for the main attributes, and one for its variants.\n> Then each connected component should only display one input and set the\n> min === max.\n>\n> Will this work?\n>\n> —\n> You are receiving this because you were mentioned.\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> <https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch.js/issues/5270>,\n> or mute the thread\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/ABo6By6AU3HlG65YyW0qgLZCiHTQ_0rVks5r6c0dgaJpZM4NaM_d>\n> .\n>\n",
